          id: 'golden-age-of-piracy',
          title: 'The Golden Age of Piracy',
          content: `The Golden Age of Piracy — roughly 1650 to 1730 — was not a period of romantic outlawry. It was a structural consequence of European imperial competition in the Atlantic. England, France, Spain, and the Netherlands were fighting for control of Caribbean trade routes, and all of them used privateers — privately owned warships licensed by a government to attack enemy shipping. The line between privateer and pirate was a legal distinction that depended entirely on who was issuing the commission and who was recognizing it.

When wars ended, privateers lost their licenses but kept their ships, their crews, and their knowledge of shipping lanes. Peacetime turned a legal combatant into an illegal one overnight. Kidd's career sits exactly on this fault line. He was commissioned, he operated, the political context shifted, and suddenly the same activities that had been sanctioned were prosecuted. The Golden Age of Piracy was not a golden age of freedom. It was a period when the rules were being rewritten and the people who had operated under the old rules were caught in the transition.`,
