          id: 'the-executed-pirate',
          title: 'The Executed Pirate',
          content: `William Kidd was hanged at Execution Dock in Wapping, London, on May 23, 1701. The execution was public, prolonged, and deliberately spectacular. The rope broke on the first attempt, and Kidd fell to the ground — alive, reportedly half-conscious. He was hauled back up and hanged a second time. His body was then coated in tar and suspended in an iron cage — a gibbet — over the Thames at Tilbury Point, where it remained for years as a warning to sailors entering and leaving the port.

The botched execution added a layer to the mythology that a clean hanging would not have. The broken rope was read by some as a sign of divine intervention — or demonic protection. The gibbeting was designed to turn a man into a symbol, and it succeeded beyond the government's intention. Kidd's dangling corpse became the image of the pirate in death — silenced, displayed, but still present, still guarding whatever secrets he took to the scaffold. The executed pirate cannot be questioned. The treasure map dies with him.`,
