          id: 'colonial-atlantic',
          title: 'Colonial Atlantic World',
          content: `Kidd's story is unintelligible without the colonial Atlantic as a system. The Atlantic world of the late seventeenth century was not a set of isolated colonies — it was a single, interconnected commercial and political network stretching from London to the Caribbean to the Indian Ocean and back. Merchants in New York financed privateers who sailed under English commissions to raid French and Mogul shipping in the Arabian Sea, with profits flowing through colonial ports that were simultaneously centers of legitimate trade and pirate fencing operations.

Kidd himself embodied this system. He was a respectable New York shipowner. His backers included some of the most powerful men in England — the Earl of Bellomont, members of the Whig ministry. His commission was signed by King William III. When the venture went wrong politically — when the ship he attacked turned out to be politically inconvenient — the same men who had financed him disavowed him. The colonial Atlantic was a system that ran on plausible deniability, and Kidd was the man who became implausible.`,
