          id: 'oak-island',
          title: 'Oak Island',
          content: `Oak Island, off the coast of Nova Scotia, has been the site of treasure-hunting expeditions since 1795, when a local teenager reportedly discovered a circular depression in the ground suggesting buried material. Over the following two centuries, excavators have found layers of log platforms, coconut fiber, putty, and what appeared to be engineered flood tunnels designed to booby-trap the pit. No treasure has been conclusively recovered, despite expenditures of millions of dollars and multiple fatalities among diggers.

Kidd is one of several candidates proposed as the original depositor — along with the Templars, Francis Bacon, and various other figures. The connection to Kidd rests on geography, timing, and the absence of better candidates. Nova Scotia was on the sailing routes between the Caribbean and the North Atlantic. Kidd operated in these waters. The pit, if it was engineered, required resources and knowledge consistent with a well-organized maritime operation. But the Oak Island mystery may ultimately be a story about treasure hunting itself — about what happens when the search becomes more elaborate than any plausible treasure could justify, and the quest takes on a life independent of its object.`,
