          id: 'moral-theater',
          title: 'Public Hanging as Moral Theater',
          content: `Public execution in the early modern world was not primarily about punishment. It was performance. The state staged the death of the criminal as a demonstration of sovereign power and moral order — a theatrical event with a script, an audience, a set, and a message. Execution Dock at Wapping was the designated stage for maritime criminals, positioned at the water's edge so that the condemned walked through crowds of sailors, merchants, and dockworkers who were meant to absorb the lesson.

The pirate execution carried a particular charge because the pirate represented a specific threat to the system: unauthorized violence and unauthorized profit on the open sea. The pirate was not merely a thief — he was a competitor. He operated outside the licensing system that gave states their monopoly on maritime force. The public hanging said: this is what happens to those who operate outside our authority. But the spectacle also created the pirate as a figure of popular fascination. The crowd that was meant to be deterred was also entertained. The gibbet that was meant to erase the pirate from memory instead fixed him there permanently — a figure suspended between law and legend, visible from the river, impossible to forget.`,
